Data Science Project¶

Author: Tyler Mittelholtz

Introduction¶

The goal of this project is to build and compare machine learning models to apply to the built in "penguins" dataset, and to show visualizations of the process.

Charts¶

This first chart is a visualization of bill length related to body mass. I expect to see a positive coefficiant, meaning the larger the penguin the longer the bill.

In [85]:

It looks like my hypothesis was correct. Visually, you can see an increase in body mass typically means longer bill length. Also all three species seem distinguishable in 3 seperate zones with little overlap.

Now to do the same relation with different y values. I expect to find the same trend is true for the others, but would be intrigued to find one that is does not follow this.

Predicting Sex using Logistic Regression¶

In [91]:
df.loc[:, 'ismale'] = df['sex'] == 'Male'

I will let "True" represent male, and "False" represent female.

In [92]:
cols = ["flipper_length_mm", "bill_length_mm"]
In [93]:
classifiers = {}
for species in df['species'].unique():
    df_species = df[df['species'] == species].copy()#I get a warning if i dont do this
    X = df_species[cols]
    y = df_species['ismale']
    
    clf = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000)
    clf.fit(X, y)
    df_species['pred'] = clf.predict(X)
    accuracy = clf.score(X, y)
    classifiers[species] = clf
    print(f"Accuracy for {species}: {accuracy * 100:.2f}%")

Accuracy for Adelie: 76.71%
Accuracy for Chinstrap: 85.29%
Accuracy for Gentoo: 84.03%

It looks like in each species, the variables are a pretty good indicator of sex, but less so in Adelie. This could imply that there is less of a difference in size between male and femal Adelie penguins.

This model is trained to predict sex based on only flipper length and bill length. At first I used all four variables in col. This got me better results, and I wanted to continue with it, but the two dimensional confusion matrix would not be representative of the models performance using just two of the variables.

Logistic Regression was a good choice for predicting sex, since the output is binary. The decision boundary creates a clear, linear boundary, where the confidence of the model being corect crosses 50%.

The RFC acheived an accuracy of 95%, which is really good. Visually it is clear that there is little overlap between species, so a high accuracy was expected I used an RFC to predict species because generally RFC's take multiple inputs well, whereas with Logistic Regression I just stuck with two. The surprising part here is that a lot of inidividual trees actually performed better than the overall model. But the entire model performed better than the average of each tree inside, so I still consider it effective. The reason for the this is the size of the dataset. RFC is more efficient with larger datasets, as some of the random trees will have a higher chance of being accidentally correct since there are fewer data points. A simpler method may have been more useful and efficient for the small penguins dataset.

label_mapping = {i: species for i, species in enumerate(species_names)}

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred, labels=list(label_mapping.keys()))

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))

plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
plt.ylabel('True label')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix')

This visualization is simple and can tell us more about the accuracy of the model. The most frequent mistake was predicting Chinstrap for an Adelie.

This graph shows how much importance each of the four features have on the output of the model. Ranking from most to least important, it goes bill length, flipper length, bill depth, then body mass. This graph, combined with the high accuracy of the model, can support any claims about differences in features between species.

Using Linear Regression to Predict Body Mass¶

My goal here is to predict body mass based on flipper length, bill length, and bill depth seperately, and compare the results.

In [111]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import r2_score
In [112]:
features = ['flipper_length_mm', 'bill_length_mm', 'bill_depth_mm']
y = df['body_mass_g']

for feature in features:
    X = df[[feature]] 
    clf = LinearRegression()
    clf.fit(X, y)
    
    y_pred = clf.predict(X)

    r2 = r2_score(y, y_pred)
    print(f"R2 score for {feature}: {r2:.2f}")
    
    plt.scatter(X, y)
    plt.plot(X, y_pred, color='red')
    plt.title(f'Linear Regression: {feature} vs Body Mass')
    plt.xlabel(feature.replace('_', ' ').title())
    plt.ylabel('Body Mass (g)')
    plt.show()

R2 score for flipper_length_mm: 0.76

R2 score for bill_length_mm: 0.35

R2 score for bill_depth_mm: 0.22

Starting with flipper length, it looks the linear regression model is the best fit, as the points seem to follow the line. An R2 score of .76 is good.

With bill length, the results are not the same. While it doesnt fit it terribly, I think that seperating by species could give more accurate results, as it seems some points follow a lower slope. The R2 score of .35 is much too low.

The bill depth results were not useful. the R2 score of .22 is also too low. The graph seems to have two seperate clusters. Given that there looks to be more points on one side, I assume its becasue one species has drastically different bill depth compare to the other two. For bill length and bill depth I will redo the linear regression models for each species seperately and see if the results are better.

In [113]:
feature = 'bill_length_mm'

species_groups = df.groupby('species')
species
for species, group in species_groups:
    X = group[[feature]]
    y = group['body_mass_g']
    
    clf = LinearRegression()
    clf.fit(X, y)  
    y_pred = clf.predict(X)
    r2 = r2_score(y, y_pred)
    print(f"R2 score for {feature} in {species}: {r2:.2f}")
    
    plt.scatter(X, y, label='Actual')
    plt.plot(X, y_pred, color='red', label='Predicted')
    plt.title(f'Linear Regression: {feature.replace("_", " ").title()} vs Body Mass for {species}')
    plt.xlabel(feature.replace('_', ' ').title())
    plt.ylabel('Body Mass (g)')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

R2 score for bill_length_mm in Adelie: 0.30

R2 score for bill_length_mm in Chinstrap: 0.26

R2 score for bill_length_mm in Gentoo: 0.44

Visibly, this fits better than all together. The R2 scores though are still pretty low. I'll conclude that linear regression does not accurately predict body mass from bill length for any species.

In [114]:

species

    r2 = r2_score(y, y_pred)

R2 score for bill_depth_mm in Adelie: 0.34

R2 score for bill_depth_mm in Chinstrap: 0.37

R2 score for bill_depth_mm in Gentoo: 0.52

Again, visually this is better, but the R2 scores are still too low. Thus we can conclude that flipper length is a better indicator of body mass than bill length and bill depth are, at least in the context of linear regression.

Summary¶

In this project, I utilized Logistic Regression to predict the sex of penguins based on bill length, and flipper length. I found the model to be fairly accurate and plotted to visualize the decision boundaries. I also used an RFC to very accurately predict species based on flipper length, bill length, bill depth, and body mass. Then used a confusion matrix and feature importance chart to find which of these four features were the most important to the models success. Lastly I used linear regression to predict body mass, and found that it did not accurately predict body mass from bill length or bill depth, but did for flipper length.
